06215nam a22011415i 9780813590332DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20182018nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135903327 a10.36019/97808135903322doi  a(DE-B1597)526122  a(OCoLC)1035633093  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a782.1/422300aHistorians on Hamilton :bHow a Blockbuster Musical Is Restaging America's Past /ced. by Renee C. Romano, Claire Bond Potter. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (396 p.) :b25 color and 6 black and whit  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmerica has gone Hamilton crazy. Lin-Manuel Miranda's Tony-winning musical has spawned sold-out performances, a triple platinum cast album, and a score so catchy that it is being used to teach U.S. history in classrooms across the country. But just how historically accurate is Hamilton? And how is the show itself making history? Historians on Hamilton brings together a collection of top scholars to explain the Hamilton phenomenon and explore what it might mean for our understanding of America's history. The contributors examine what the musical got right, what it got wrong, and why it matters. Does Hamilton's hip-hop take on the Founding Fathers misrepresent our nation's past, or does it offer a bold positive vision for our nation's future? Can a musical so unabashedly contemporary and deliberately anachronistic still communicate historical truths about American culture and politics? And is Hamilton as revolutionary as its creators and many commentators claim? Perfect for students, teachers, theatre fans, hip-hop heads, and history buffs alike, these short and lively essays examine why Hamilton became an Obama-era sensation and consider its continued relevance in the age of Trump. Whether you are a fan or a skeptic, you will come away from this collection with a new appreciation for the meaning and importance of the Hamilton phenomenon.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAlexander Hamilton.  aHamilaria.  aHamilton.  aLin-Manuel Miranda.  abroadway.  ahip hop.  ahip-hop.  ahistory.  amusical.  arap.  atheater.1 aAdelman, Joseph M.1 aAdelman, Joseph M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllgor, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllgor, Catherine.1 aBond Potter, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCullen, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCullen, Jim.1 aFreeman, Joanne B.1 aFreeman, Joanne B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarris, Leslie M.1 aHarris, Leslie M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerrera, Brian Eugenio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerrera, Brian Eugenio.1 aHerrera, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerrera, Patricia.1 aHogeland, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHogeland, William.1 aMonteiro, Lyra D.1 aMonteiro, Lyra D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO'Malley, Michael.1 aO'Malley, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPasley, Jeffrey L.1 aPasley, Jeffrey L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPotter, Claire Bond, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPotter, Claire Bond.1 aRomano, Renee C.1 aRomano, Renee C., econtr